Project Deliverable - Final¶

Introduction¶

This dataset contains information on 9,506 online clients for Vangarrd Stores in America. This data contains purchaing behavior from the past 12 months. This data includes different sections that have been applied to the clients when purchasing as well as different deographical characteristics and which platforms were used when purchasing.

Goal:¶

The goal of this project is to analyze the dataset and create appropriate models to predict future sales

Key Questions: What effect does the loyalty_group have on sales? Does frequency or consistancy contribute to this? What variable is most influencing the cummulative sales?

Data Information For this data structure, there are 9,506 rows of client information involving sales and client characterisitcs divided into 16 variables. For this project we will be utalizing the 10 variables below.

  • CLIENT_ID: An index for client identification
  • CUMMSALES_LAST12MONTHS: Cumulative sales over the last 12 weeks
  • FREQUENCY_LAST12MONTHS: Purchases made during the previous twelve weeks
  • AVERAGE_TICKET: Average transaction value over the past twelve weeks
  • RECENCY: Number of days since the most recent purchase
  • CONSISTENCY: Total number of weeks within the last 12 weeks in which the consumer has made a purchase
  • BRANCH: The branch that the consumer commonly visits or where they frequently collect orders
  • LOYALTY_GROUP: Customer segmentation based on purchase frequency
  • GENERE: Gender identity of customer
  • MOSTUSED_PLATFORM: The platform the customer most frequently uses to place orders

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

When examining the dataset, we can see there are a few missing values. It shows that MARITAL_STATUS and GENDER both have 1 missing data point. BIRTH_DATE and AGE have both 1158 missing data points. I have excluded these variables from my model, so I don't see this being a problem. There seems to be a few extreme outliers as well from the boxplots below. Mainly in the cummulative sales, frequency in the last 12 weeks, and the average ticket.

I chose FREQUENCY_LAST12WEEKS, AVERAGE_TICKET, RECENCY, CONSISTENCY, LOYALTY_GROUP, and MOSTUSED_PLATFORM as predictors because looking at these sections will show the outcome of the sales and what is driving their sales. I have CUMMSALES_LAST12WEEKS as the outcome for the questions because I would assume that the company's top priority is what is driving the sales.

Preproccessing Data¶

Variable Modification¶

Since I chose to create a linear regression model, I hot-encoded the two variables: MOSTUSED_PLATFORM and LOYALTY_GROUP. I did this to allow the model to read the data by creating numeric values for the categorical data which also created more columns for each qualitative category.

Excluded Variables¶

As for the variables that I excluded: CLIENT_ID, BRANCH, SEGMENT_1, PRICE_GROUP, SEGMENT_2, GENDER, MARITAL_STATUS, BIRTH_DATE, AGE. I chose to exclude these because I went through each variable and comparing them to the questions that I created and found that they woundn't provide useful information to provide insight to the outcome. I also analyzed the correlation matrix to find which variables have a strong correlation to the outcome variable.

Centering and Scaling¶

For this dataset I used scikit-learn to scale the numeric values of the data to prevent variables on a larger scale to overcome those in a smaller scale.

#visualize categorical data
def visualize_categorical_variables(database, max_categories=20):
    """
    Automatically visualize all non-numerical (categorical) variables in a DataFrame.
    Generates count plots for each categorical variable with a reasonable number of unique values.
    
    Parameters:
    - df: pandas DataFrame containing the data to be visualized.
    - max_categories: Maximum number of unique categories to visualize for each variable. 
                      Variables with more categories than this will be skipped to avoid cluttered plots.
    """
    # Identify categorical columns
    categorical_columns = database.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category', 'bool']).columns
    
    sns.set_style("whitegrid")
    
    for col in categorical_columns:
        if database[col].nunique() > max_categories:
            print(f'Skipping {col} as it has more than {max_categories} unique categories.')
            continue
        
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
        sns.countplot(y=col, data=database, order = database[col].value_counts().index)
        plt.title(f'Count Plot of {col}')
        plt.xlabel('Count')
        plt.ylabel(col)
        plt.show()

visualize_categorical_variables(database, max_categories=20)

Understanding the Data¶

Showing these graphs, we can see the different relationships between the variables. With CLIENT_ID being an identifier, I decided to drop this variable because it has nothing to do with the data itself. The BRANCH variable has too many values for me to include in the predictors.

When looking at the correlation matrix, specifically the CUMMSALES_LAST12WEEKS, we can see that FREQUENCY_LAST12WEEKS, AVERAGE_TICKET, and CONSISTENCY all have a strong correlation with the outcome variable, therefore we will include those in our predictors.

Outliers¶

We can seem from these graphs that there are a few extreme outliers in cummulative sales, frequency, and average ticket. I chose to keep these outliers in the dataset because even though they are extreme, I still believe them to be true data points just by the kind of variables they are.

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=True, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

PCA¶

We could use PCA because the data has a moderate correlation with some of its features. If you recall the corellation matrix I created earlier, we can see though that most of the variables don't correlate well with each other most of them being around 0.3. Since only a few of the variables are strongly correlated, it wouldn't be a good decision to use PCA in this case because it wouldn't do a good job of reducing the data.

Clustering¶

I don't believe using a cluster analysis would be beneficial in the case of this data. If you recall to the pair plot that was made for the data, you can see there is no evidence of clustering in those graphs. Also the fact that my data is hot-encoded, this wouldn't do well with the cluster analysis. Plus the data already has a class label (LOYALTY_GROUP) so a clustering analysis is not necessary.

If we look at the data and what would be most appropriate to assess each model, I would say the RMSE is the most important in this case. The whole point of building these models is to predict future sales and to find out what is driving these sales. Each of these metrics are used for different things, but in this case I would say RMSE would be best because this tell us the difference in what the predicted cummualtive sales and what the actual cummulative sales would be.

MAE would be good to use since we have quite a few outliers in our data and MAE does a good job of making sure the model doesn't have any outlier predictions. The reason I don't think it's the best option is because if it makes a bad prediction, putting the prediction through the function would increase the error.

Adjusted R-squared is a great tool, I believe the company would rather see profit numbers over percentage numbers when reading the accuracy of the model.

Conclusion¶

Model Rank¶

  1. Gradient Boosting Model
  2. Random Forest Model
  3. Decision Tree
  4. Support Vector Machine Model
  5. Neural Network Model
  6. Lasso Regression Model
  7. Linear Regression Model
  8. Generalized Additive Model

Looking at the reporting results above we can see that the Gradient Boosting Model is ranked as the top model. We can see that is because it has the lowest combined RMSE and MAE score meaning this model is the most accurate and the adjusted R-squared is of the highest varience. So, in conclusion the Gradient Boosting model would be the best pick because this model shows how strong the relationship is between the predictors and the outcome variable and that it's the most accurate.

The Random Forest Model is fairly similar to the Gradient Boosting Model in terms of similar RMSE and MAE values and even the Adjusted R-squared is close to the GBM value, so the Random Forest would be a good model to pick as well if the company would rather go with this model. This model was also quicker in terms of fitting the model.

The Decision Tree looks to have doubled in the RMSE and MAE values compared to the Random Forest model so based on that alone, I wouldn't recommend the company use the Decision Tree Model because the accuracy isn't too great. The book even explains that decision trees aren't known for being the most accurate models. (James, 2023, pg. 338) But they are very easy to explain to someone, imitates human decision-making. (James, 2023, pg. 349)

As for the SVM Model it's dead center in terms of ranking, but the time it takes to run this model is the slowest of all the models combined. That being said with this type of model wouldn't be efficient for this company because of the size of the company's data and the time they need to run this model. In real life instances, the book even says that not many people use SVM because the classes must be divided by a linear boundary. (James, 2023, pg. 374)

The Neural Network has a pretty low variance, and the RMSE and MAE are high as well, so I wouldn't reccomend using this model.

Out of all the Adjusted R-squared values we can see that they all have a relatively strong correlation except for the Linear Regression Model being at 0.33. Even though the GAM Model has a higher Adjusted R-squared than Linear Regression, the RMSE and MAE values are higher in GAM than the Linear Regression Model so the GAM Model is less accurate. We expected the Linear Regression to not be the greatest model on this list from the book stating that this model isn't a significant predictor anymore and that newer, more advanced models have been made since then. (James, 2023, pg. 92) In terms of adjusted R-squared GAM is significantly higher because as the book suggests, GAM can fit the model with non-linear relationships therfore making it more accurate. (James, 2023, pg. 316)

Variables¶

I believe there are some very strong correlations to the outcome variable. The top variables that showed the biggest correlation in numbers were: FREQUENCY_LAST12MONTHS, AVERAGE_TICKET, and LOYALTY_GROUP_Vip. If you remeber me stating earilier with the correlation matrix you could see that this still stands true.

You can also see from the table I created in reporting results that the top three in the variable aggregate importance are AVERAGE_TICKET, FREQUENCY_LAST12MONTHS, and LOYALTY_GROUP_Vip. These three always had the highest coefficiants and the highest variable importance when checked.

Model Recommendation¶

I believe that the Gradient Boosting Model would be the model that would have best predictive performance because this type of model does a great job with accuracy, has the highest varience, and fits the model in a decent amount of time. From the book, it goes to explain that this type of model makes multiple decision trees making this model learn slower, but also more accurate and I believe that is why it is at the top. (James, 2023, pg. 355)

I would recommend the Random Forest Model for a good enough solution quickly because of how similar it is to the Gradient Boosting Model in terms of accuracy and varience, all while fitting the model in a timely manner.

This company likely needs a fast, accurate model to determine future sales and trends on what is effecting these sales, so I believe they should go with the Random Forest Model to optimise their companies profits.
